# üëã Welcome to your Knowledge Garden

[[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™®  üå≥  Obsidian Garden\|ü™®  üå≥  Obsidian Garden]] is a open-source guide to creating your own [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üå≥ Digital Garden\|üå≥  Digital Garden]] with [Obsidian](https://obsidian.md).

The garden is contained within in it's own [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üóÉ Knowledge Management\|üóÉ  Knowledge Management System]] - designed as a template for you to learn the basics of working with [[üìá Terms/ü™® Obsidian/ü™® Obsidian\|ü™®  Obsidian]] and extend and remix in to your own.

## üíæ Installing The Guide

The easiest way to start is clone [this GitHub repository](https://github.com/tanepiper/obsidian-garden) containing the most up to date version, or download it as a zip file.

> `git clone https://github.com/tanepiper/obsidian-garden.git`

Then you can open in [[üìá Terms/ü™® Obsidian/ü™® Obsidian\|ü™® Obsidian]] - make sure the [[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™® Obsidian/üîå Plugins & üåà Theme\|üîå  Plugins & üåà  Theme]] are also installed.

> ‚ö†Ô∏è The Obsidian Garden is currently in active development and evolving - it's being developed in the open but is subject to changes, and may contain broken links and errors

## üîó Creating Connections

üí° Great ideas happen when there is an [[üìá Terms/üí° Concepts/Connection\|connection]] between knowledge and inspiration.

For thousands of years humans have tried to make sense of the world around them. Scientists, philosophers, writers, and even you and [[üë®‚Äçüëß‚Äçüë¶ People/üßëüèª‚Äçüíª Tane Piper\|I]] try to categorise it, understand how it works and create [[üìá Terms/üí° Concepts/System\|systems]] that allow us to store and process this knowledge.

Each time this has allowed new ideas to form, adding to the collective [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/Knowledge Graph\|Knowledge Graph]] from which more build on - but in our modern world there are so many distractions and so much new information to process that it can be really hard to see the [[üìá Terms/ü™® Obsidian/Link\|links]] between things.

From our own minds, to a collection of half-filled notebooks in a drawer and from a bookshelf of unread books to your nearest library - all contain the inspiration we need to think of our next great idea.

## üí© Avoiding Information Rot

‚õîÔ∏è When it come to storing our ideas - in the worst-case we use only our brain.

When we do this, an idea can only exist within the boundaries of our own imagination. No one else yet knows about your idea (unless there is a [Multiple Discovery](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_discovery) - but this also means you're losing out).

Without communicating this idea the first real risk in [[üìá Terms/üí° Concepts/Information Rot\|Information Rot]] is you!

In the west, oral tradition is unreliable - telling people about your idea is great, but passed on information tends to be unreliable and incomplete. Only the source is truly reliable, and even then at risk of forgetting details.

The only way to truly capture an idea is to write it down, draw it, or record it. Even here there's a risk that without one single place to put it all - you will miss out on [[üìá Terms/üí° Concepts/Connection\|connecting]] it all together.

In [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üóÉ Knowledge Management\|Knowledge Management]] systems there is concept of the _"second brain"_ - a dynamic and visual hard drive that we can consciously put our stream of thoughts and ideas in to.

On top of this we build the [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üå≥ Digital Garden\|üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üå≥ Digital Garden]] idea - in this guide known as the **Knowledge Garden** - this is not a new idea, instead we build on this concept and use it as a base template to show a working system.

## üß† Creating a second brain

Using [[üìá Terms/ü™® Obsidian/ü™® Obsidian\|Obsidian]] and this guide you can use it to create your own system - either by extending, or creating your own from scratch.

By extending Obsidian with [[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™® Obsidian/üîå Plugins & üåà Theme\|üîå Plugins and a üåà Theme]] we can start to build with more functionality for creating and querying the underlying data.

This guide is designed to get you starting in understanding why a [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/üóÉ Knowledge Management\|Knowledge Garden]] is useful and to help reduce the learning curve.

## üå∫ Letting Ideas Flourish

‚è≥ Like a real garden, good ideas need nurtured and take time to grow - but can reap rewards when cared for correctly.

To escape the distractions of life we can visit our [[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™®  üå≥  Obsidian Garden\|Obsidian Garden]] to reconnect with [[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™¥ Sowing Your Garden/üå± Planting Seeds\|üå± new]] and [[ü™¥ Grow Room\|ü™¥ old]] knowledge and create [[üìá Terms/ü™® Obsidian/Link\|links]] between them so we can see the [[üìá Terms/üß† Knowledge Systems/Knowledge Graph\|Knowledge Graph]] that connects them.

Adding enhanced richness with `#tags` and `Variables::` allows us to perform [[searches\|searches]] and [[build queries\|build queries]] that allow us to [[üë©‚Äçüåæ Gardening Tips/ü™¥ Sowing Your Garden/üéØ  Create Custom Dashboards\|üéØ Create Custom Dashboards]] and code blocks that let us see through the overgrowth of all the data - display tables, and lists - both basic to do items.

Every [[üë®‚Äçüëß‚Äçüë¶ People\|person's]] garden is different - some are neatly manecured and ordered, while some are more organic and wild - both need nurturing and tending too.

### üèÑ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è Suggested flow

The suggested flow shows one way of thinking how items are handled - when you have an idea (or want to collect a link, a picture of a doodle, create a contact) you can start with a [[‚è£ Templates/üóí Basic Note\|‚è£ Templates/üóí Basic Note]] - or select a more detailed ‚è£ Template.

All items start in the üå± Seed Box - an inbox for all items that need [[triage\|triage]].  Items can then go into the immediate ü™µ Backlog, or be categorised and filed - once items have been created they create new opportunities for new ideas to be created.

```mermaid
graph LR
	Idea((Get Idea)) -- Braindump --> Notes([Create Seeds])
	Notes --> Triage{Triage}
	Triage --> Dump
	Triage --> Backlog
	Backlog --> Dump
	Backlog --> Organise
	Triage --> Organise{{Organise Items}}
	Organise -- Create --> Person
	Person --> Research>Conduct Research]
	Organise -- Create --> Term
	Term --> Research
	Organise -- Create --> Todo
	Todo -- Discover --> Idea
	Research -- Question --> Person
	Research -- Discover --> Idea
	Research -- Formulate --> Create
	Create -- Iterate --> Idea
```
